2026-03-28 20:49:20,282 | INFO | readme_agent_api | [AGENT] Tool call: {'tool': 'create_or_update_file', 'input': {'path': 'README.md', 'message': 'docs: add README generated by readme-agent', 'repo': 'Glass-Clustering', 'branch': 'main', 'content': '# Glass Clustering\n\n> Unsupervised clustering of glass types based on chemical composition and physical properties.\n\n## 🧠 Overview\n\nThis project focuses on performing unsupervised clustering on a glass dataset. The primary goal is to identify inherent groupings of similar glass types without any prior knowledge of their classifications. This helps in understanding the underlying structure of the glass data based on its chemical composition and physical properties.\n\n## 🔨 What I Built\n\nI built a Jupyter Notebook that performs a comprehensive clustering analysis on glass data. The notebook demonstrates the following core features:\n\n-   **Data Exploration and Preprocessing**: Initial analysis of features like \'Calcium\' (Ca) and \'Refractive Index\' (RI), followed by standardization of all features crucial for distance-based algorithms.\n-   **Dimensionality Reduction**: Utilizes Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to reduce the dimensionality of the data, enabling 2D visualization of clusters.\n-   **K-Means Clustering**: Implements the K-Means algorithm to group glass samples into distinct clusters.\n-   **Optimal Cluster Determination**: Employs the "elbow method" (inertia) and silhouette scores to evaluate and select the most appropriate number of clusters.\n-   **Cluster Visualization**: Visualizes the identified clusters using interactive plots (Plotly Express) and static plots (Matplotlib, Seaborn).\n\n## 💭 Thought Process\n\nI approached the problem of glass clustering by first exploring the dataset, noting the presence of a \'Type of glass\' column which I decided to set aside for unsupervised learning, treating it as ground truth for later evaluation rather than a training feature.\n\nInitially, I focused on two highly correlated features, \'Ca\' and \'RI\', for a preliminary clustering exercise. This allowed for an easier visual understanding before expanding to the full feature set. A key decision was to standardize the data using `StandardScaler` prior to applying K-Means and PCA, as distance-based algorithms are sensitive to feature scales.\n\nTo determine the optimal number of clusters for K-Means, I leveraged both the elbow method (by plotting inertia for various `k` values) and silhouette scores. While the elbow method provided a good initial estimate, silhouette scores offered a more robust metric for validation. PCA was instrumental in visualizing the high-dimensional data in a more interpretable 2D space, which was crucial for understanding the separation and distribution of the identified clusters. The use of a `Pipeline` (or `make_pipeline`) for `StandardScaler` and `KMeans` streamlined the process and prevented data leakage.\n\n## 🛠️ Tools & Tech Stack\n\n| Layer      | Technology               |\n|------------|--------------------------|\n| Language   | Python 3.x               |\n| Data Analysis | Numpy, Pandas            |\n| Visualization | Matplotlib, Seaborn, Plotly Express |\n| Machine Learning | Scikit-learn (StandardScaler, PCA, KMeans, Pipeline, make_pipeline, silhouette_score) |\n\n## 🚀 Getting Started\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Python 3.x installed.\n- Access to a Jupyter Notebook environment (e.g., Jupyter Lab, VS Code with Jupyter extension).\n\n### Installation\n\n1.  **Clone the repository:**\n    ```bash\n    git clone https://github.com/rashadmin/Glass-Clustering.git\n    cd Glass-Clustering\n    ```\n\n2.  **Install the necessary Python libraries:**\n    ```bash\n    pip install numpy pandas matplotlib seaborn plotly scikit-learn\n    ```\n\n### Data\nEnsure the `glass.csv` dataset is present in the root directory of the project, alongside the notebook.\n\n### Run\n\n1.  **Open the Jupyter Notebook:**\n    ```bash\n    jupyter notebook Glass_Clustering.ipynb\n    ```\n    or open it via your preferred IDE.\n\n2.  **Execute the cells sequentially** within the `Glass_Clustering.ipynb` notebook to perform the clustering analysis.\n\n## 📖 Usage\n\nThe `Glass_Clustering.ipynb` notebook provides a step-by-step guide through the entire clustering process:\n\n### Example 1: Loading and Initial Data Exploration\n\nThe notebook begins by loading the `glass.csv` dataset and displaying its first few rows and basic statistics.\n\n```python\nimport pandas as pd\nglass_df = pd.read_csv(\'glass.csv\')\nprint(glass_df.head())\nprint(glass_df.info())\n```\n\n### Example 2: Performing K-Means Clustering with PCA\n\nAfter preprocessing, the data is fed into a pipeline that scales the features and applies K-Means, with PCA for visualization.\n\n```python\nfrom sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\nfrom sklearn.decomposition import PCA\nfrom sklearn.cluster import KMeans\nfrom sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline\nimport plotly.express as px\n\n# Assuming X contains your preprocessed features\n# scaler = StandardScaler()\n# pca = PCA(n_components=2)\n# kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, random_state=42)\n\n# pipeline = make_pipeline(scaler, pca, kmeans)\n# cluster_labels = pipeline.fit_predict(X)\n\n# Visualize clusters (example using Plotly Express, as seen in the notebook)\n# fig = px.scatter(x=X_pca[:, 0], y=X_pca[:, 1], color=cluster_labels, title="Glass Clusters (PCA-reduced)")\n# fig.show()\n```\n\n## 📚 Resources\n\n-   [Scikit-learn Clustering Documentation](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/clustering.html) — Official documentation for clustering algorithms in scikit-learn.\n-   [Scikit-learn PCA Documentation](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/decomposition.html#PCA) — Details on Principal Component Analysis.\n-   [Pandas Documentation](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/) — Comprehensive guide for data manipulation and analysis with Pandas.\n-   [Plotly Express Documentation](https://plotly.com/python/plotly-express/) — Interactive plotting library for Python.\n', 'owner': 'rashadmin'}}
