2026-03-30 21:08:50,248 | INFO | readme_agent_api | [AGENT] Tool call: {'tool': 'create_or_update_file', 'input': {'repo': 'hospital_agent', 'branch': 'master', 'owner': 'rashadmin', 'sha': '1c5794fb40442c3b5daa07a0cc7b1bae06a6d912', 'path': 'README.md', 'content': '# Hospital Agent\n\n> A reactive LangGraph agent that processes requests from Redis streams.\n\n## 🧠 Overview\n\nThis project provides a robust agent designed to interact with a distributed system by consuming tasks from Redis streams. It leverages LangGraph to manage complex conversational states and orchestrate asynchronous request processing, making it suitable for event-driven architectures where agents need to react to external triggers.\n\n## 🔨 What I Built\n\nThe core of this project is a stateful LangGraph agent capable of:\n\n-   **Redis Stream Integration:** Continuously listening for incoming requests on a specified Redis stream using a dedicated background thread.\n-   **State Management with LangGraph:** Utilizing `StateGraph` to maintain the agent\'s internal state, including a queue of processed requests and associated metadata.\n-   **Dynamic Response Generation:** A `responder` node within the graph intelligently determines whether to send a response based on the current context, enabling conditional replies.\n-   **Modular and Testable Architecture:** The agent\'s components are structured for clarity and maintainability, with comprehensive unit and integration tests ensuring reliable operation.\n\n## 💭 Thought Process\n\nMy primary goal was to create an agent that could asynchronously handle requests from an external messaging system without blocking its main execution. I opted for LangGraph\'s `StateGraph` as it provides a powerful abstraction for managing complex, multi-step agent workflows and state transitions.\n\nA key design decision was to use a background thread to listen to Redis streams. This allowed the LangGraph runtime to remain free for processing, while new requests were seamlessly ingested into the agent\'s state. I implemented a reducer function (`add`) to efficiently update the list of requests within the graph\'s state.\n\nFor testing, I integrated `pytest` with `AnyIO` to facilitate asynchronous testing of the graph\'s behavior. This ensures that the agent\'s interactions with Redis and its internal state management are robust and correct under various conditions. The use of `__all__` in the `agent` package\'s `__init__.py` was a deliberate choice to clearly define the public API, improving module maintainability and discoverability.\n\n## 🛠️ Tools & Tech Stack\n\n| Layer       | Technology        |\n| :---------- | :---------------- |\n| Language    | Python 3.x        |\n| Framework   | LangGraph         |\n| Core Library| LangChain Core    |\n| Messaging   | Redis             |\n| Testing     | pytest, AnyIO     |\n| Utilities   | typing\\_extensions, threading, time, dataclasses |\n\n## 🚀 Getting Started\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Python >= 3.x\n- Redis server running on `localhost:6379`\n- A Redis stream named `requests`\n\n### Installation\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/rashadmin/hospital_agent.git\ncd hospital_agent\npip install -r requirements.txt\n```\n\n### Environment Variables\n\nThe agent might implicitly rely on API keys for LLMs. While not explicitly in the provided summaries, a `GEMINI_API_KEY` is a common requirement for LangChain/LangGraph agents.\n\nCreate a `.env` file (if applicable):\n\n```env\nGEMINI_API_KEY=your_gemini_api_key_here\n```\n\n### Run\n\nSpecific run instructions for the agent were not provided in the summaries. Typically, a LangGraph agent would be invoked via a Python script. An example of how the graph is invoked in tests (`test_agent_simple_passthrough`) suggests:\n\n```python\n# This is a conceptual example based on test invocation\nfrom src.agent.graph import graph\n\n# To run the agent, you would typically invoke the graph\n# with an initial state or input.\n# The background listener for Redis streams would run independently.\n\n# Example of invoking the graph with a simple input (as seen in tests):\n# async def main():\n#     result = await graph.ainvoke({"input": "Hello"})\n#     print(result)\n#\n# if __name__ == "__main__":\n#     import asyncio\n#     asyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nThe agent is designed to listen to Redis streams, so ensure Redis is running with the `requests` stream available.\n\n## 📖 Usage\n\nThe Hospital Agent functions by continuously monitoring a Redis stream for incoming requests. Once a request is received, it\'s processed through the LangGraph state machine.\n\n### Example 1: Basic Graph Invocation (for testing/direct input)\n\nWhile the primary mode of operation is via Redis streams, the graph can be directly invoked for testing or specific scenarios.\n\n```python\nfrom src.agent.graph import graph\nimport asyncio\n\nasync def run_example_invocation():\n    # This simulates an initial input to the graph,\n    # distinct from requests coming from Redis streams.\n    # The actual processing logic would then follow.\n    initial_state = {"input": "Process this request from direct invocation"}\n    result = await graph.ainvoke(initial_state)\n    print("Graph Invocation Result:", result)\n\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    asyncio.run(run_example_invocation())\n```\n\n### Example 2: Interacting via Redis (Conceptual)\n\nTo interact with the agent as intended, you would publish messages to the `requests` Redis stream. The agent\'s background listener would pick these up.\n\n```python\nimport redis\nimport time\n\n# Connect to Redis\nr = redis.Redis(host=\'localhost\', port=6379, db=0)\n\n# Publish a message to the \'requests\' stream\nmessage_id = r.xadd(\'requests\', {\'task\': \'admit_patient\', \'patient_id\': \'12345\'})\nprint(f"Published message {message_id} to \'requests\' stream.")\n\n# Wait a bit for the agent to process (conceptual)\ntime.sleep(5)\n\n# If the agent is configured to respond, you might check another stream\n# or a specific key for the response. (This part depends on agent\'s response mechanism)\n# For example, if there\'s a \'responses\' stream:\n# responses = r.xreadgroup(\'mygroup\', \'myconsumer\', {\'responses\': \'>\'}, count=1, block=100)\n# if responses:\n#     print("Agent Response:", responses)\n```\n\n## 📚 Resources\n\n-   [LangGraph Documentation](https://langgraph.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) — Agent framework\n-   [Redis Streams](https://redis.io/docs/latest/develop/data-structures/streams/) — Distributed messaging\n-   [Python threading](https://docs.python.org/3/library/threading.html) — Concurrency in Python\n-   [LangChain Expression Language (LCEL) config](https://python.langchain.com/docs/expression_language/config/) — LangChain configuration details\n-   [Pytest Documentation](https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/) — Python testing framework\n-   [AnyIO Documentation](https://anyio.readthedocs.io/en/stable/) — Asynchronous I/O for Python\n-   [LangSmith Testing](https://docs.smith.langchain.com/tracing/testing/) — Tracing and testing for LangChain applications\n\n## 📄 License\n\nMIT © rashadmin\n', 'message': 'docs: add README generated by readme-agent'}}
