2026-03-30 21:26:44,436 | INFO | readme_agent_api | [AGENT] Tool call: {'tool': 'create_or_update_file', 'input': {'content': '# Hospital Agent\n\n> A reactive agent system built with LangGraph that processes requests from Redis streams.\n\n## 🧠 Overview\n\nThis project implements a reactive agent designed to operate within a distributed system. It leverages LangGraph to manage conversational state and task processing, while integrating with Redis streams to asynchronously receive and queue requests. The agent\'s primary purpose is to listen for incoming tasks, process them according to its defined graph logic, and conditionally send responses back, making it suitable for event-driven architectures.\n\n## 🔨 What I Built\n\nThe core of this project is a LangGraph stateful graph that acts as an intelligent agent. It is capable of:\n\n-   **Asynchronous Request Handling:** Continuously listens for new requests from a designated Redis stream using a background thread, ensuring non-blocking operation.\n-   **State Management:** Utilizes LangGraph\'s `StateGraph` to maintain and update the agent\'s internal state, including a queue of incoming requests.\n-   **Conditional Response Generation:** Features a `responder` node that intelligently decides whether to formulate and send a response based on the current context and processing status.\n-   **Modular Agent Design:** The agent\'s public interface is clearly defined, exposing the main graph object for easy integration into other applications.\n\n## 💭 Thought Process\n\nMy approach to building this agent focused on creating a robust and reactive system. I chose LangGraph because of its powerful state management and ability to define complex, multi-step agent behaviors. Integrating with Redis streams was a key decision to enable a distributed, event-driven architecture, allowing the agent to passively listen for tasks rather than being actively polled. To achieve this, I decided to use a background thread for continuous Redis stream consumption, feeding events into the LangGraph state. This bypasses the typical direct LangGraph node invocation for initial data ingestion, making the agent truly reactive.\n\nA challenge encountered was ensuring careful state management and thread synchronization, especially when mixing background threads with the main LangGraph runtime. While the `state_lock` was introduced, its consistent application across all state modifications required careful consideration to prevent race conditions. Another interesting aspect was designing the `responder` node to make context-aware decisions about sending responses, adding a layer of intelligence to the agent\'s output.\n\n## 🛠️ Tools & Tech Stack\n\n| Layer           | Technology        |\n|-----------------|-------------------|\n| Language        | Python 3.x        |\n| Framework       | LangGraph         |\n| Core Libraries  | LangChain_Core    |\n| Messaging       | Redis             |\n| Utilities       | typing_extensions |\n| Concurrency     | threading, time   |\n| Data Structures | dataclasses       |\n| Testing         | pytest, AnyIO     |\n| Tracing         | LangSmith         |\n\n## 🚀 Getting Started\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Python >= 3.x\n- Redis server running (default: `localhost:6379`)\n\n### Installation\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/rashadmin/hospital_agent.git\ncd hospital_agent\npip install -r requirements.txt\n```\n\n### Run\n\nTo run the agent, you would typically execute the main graph file. Ensure your Redis server is active.\n\n```bash\npython -m src.agent\n```\n\n### Testing\n\nThe project includes both unit and integration tests.\n\n```bash\npytest\n```\n\n## 📖 Usage\n\nThe agent listens for requests on a Redis stream named \'requests\'. You can interact with it by pushing messages to this stream.\n\n### Example: Pushing a Request to Redis\n\n```python\nimport redis\nimport json\nimport time\n\nr = redis.Redis(host=\'localhost\', port=6379, db=0)\n\n# Example request\nrequest_data = {\n    "task_id": "12345",\n    "prompt": "Summarize the patient\'s medical history for the last month.",\n    "patient_id": "P001"\n}\n\n# Push the request to the \'requests\' stream\nr.xadd(\'requests\', {\'data\': json.dumps(request_data)})\nprint(f"Sent request: {request_data}")\n\n# You might need to wait for the agent to process and potentially respond\ntime.sleep(5)\n# You would then check for responses in a designated response stream or log\n```\n\n### Example: Invoking the Graph Programmatically (for testing/direct interaction)\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\nfrom src.agent.graph import graph # Assuming graph is directly importable\n\nasync def main():\n    # Example input for direct invocation\n    result = await graph.ainvoke({"requests": [{"task_id": "67890", "content": "Process this item."}]})\n    print(result)\n\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    asyncio.run(main())\n```\n\n## 📚 Resources\n\n-   [LangGraph Documentation](https://langgraph.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) — Agent framework\n-   [LangChain Expression Language (LCEL) Config](https://python.langchain.com/docs/expression_language/config/) — Configuration for LangChain components\n-   [Redis Streams Documentation](https://redis.io/docs/latest/develop/data-structures/streams/) — Redis data structure for messaging\n-   [Python `threading` Documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/threading.html) — Python\'s threading module\n-   [Pytest Documentation](https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/) — Python testing framework\n-   [AnyIO Documentation](https://anyio.readthedocs.io/en/stable/) — Asynchronous I/O bridge\n-   [LangSmith Testing Documentation](https://docs.smith.langchain.com/tracing/testing/) — LangSmith integration for testing\n\n## 📄 License\n\nMIT © [rashadmin](https://github.com/rashadmin)\n', 'owner': 'rashadmin', 'sha': '5bd2dd24a19f19c1f7c3d9e7f39279b72a81c934', 'path': 'README.md', 'repo': 'hospital_agent', 'message': 'docs: add README generated by readme-agent', 'branch': 'main'}}
