2026-03-30 22:11:13,190 | INFO | readme_agent_api | [AGENT] Tool call: {'tool': 'create_or_update_file', 'input': {'owner': 'rashadmin', 'path': 'README.md', 'message': 'docs: add README generated by readme-agent', 'repo': 'codecreator', 'branch': 'main', 'content': "# Code Creator\n\n> A Flask application designed for bootstrapping and organizing modular web applications.\n\n## 🧠 Overview\n\nThis project serves as a foundational Flask web application, structured to facilitate the creation and management of code-related functionalities. It leverages Flask's application factory pattern to ensure a clean, scalable, and organized application structure, making it suitable for developers looking to build modular web services.\n\n## 🔨 What I Built\n\nThe core of this project is a robust Flask application factory, designed to handle the initial setup and configuration of the web application. Key aspects include:\n\n-   **Modular Application Structure:** Utilizes Flask blueprints to organize different parts of the application into distinct, manageable modules.\n-   **Configuration Management:** Sets up the application to load configurations effectively, allowing for different environments (development, production) to be easily managed.\n-   **Extension Initialization:** Provides a clear pattern for initializing Flask extensions, although many are commented out by default, allowing for easy integration of new functionalities.\n\n## 💭 Thought Process\n\nI approached this project with a focus on creating a well-structured and maintainable Flask application. The decision to use the application factory pattern was crucial for ensuring the scalability and modularity of the codebase. By centralizing the application setup in `app/__init__.py`, I aimed to make it easier to manage configurations, register blueprints, and initialize extensions, which are common pain points in larger Flask projects. This design choice promotes code organization and simplifies testing and deployment processes.\n\n## 🛠️ Tools & Tech Stack\n\n| Layer    | Technology |\n|:---------|:-----------|\n| Language | Python     |\n| Framework| Flask      |\n\n## 🚀 Getting Started\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Python 3.x\n- pip (Python package installer)\n\n### Installation\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/rashadmin/codecreator.git\ncd codecreator\npip install Flask\n# If there's a requirements.txt, use:\n# pip install -r requirements.txt\n```\n\n### Environment Variables\n\nIf your application requires specific environment variables (e.g., for configuration), create a `.env` file in the root directory:\n\n```env\nFLASK_APP=app/__init__.py\nFLASK_ENV=development\n```\n\n### Run\n\n```bash\nflask run\n```\n\n## 📖 Usage\n\nOnce the Flask application is running, you can access it through your web browser, typically at `http://127.0.0.1:5000/`. The specific routes and functionalities will depend on the blueprints registered within the application.\n\n### Example: Basic Application Start\n\n```bash\n# Set environment variables (if not already set in .env)\nexport FLASK_APP=app/__init__.py\nexport FLASK_ENV=development\n\n# Run the application\nflask run\n```\n\n## 📚 Resources\n\n-   [Flask Documentation](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/latest/) — The official documentation for the Flask web framework.\n\n## 📄 License\n\nMIT © [rashadmin](https://github.com/rashadmin)\n"}}
