2026-03-30 22:18:30,030 | INFO | readme_agent_api | [AGENT] Tool call: {'tool': 'create_or_update_file', 'input': {'content': '# CodeCreator\n\n> A Flask web application that serves as an application factory, responsible for creating and configuring the Flask app instance and registering blueprints.\n\n## 🧠 Overview\n\nCodeCreator is a Flask-based web application designed with an application factory pattern. Its primary purpose is to provide a centralized and organized way to set up the Flask application, manage configuration, and register modular components using Flask Blueprints. This approach promotes maintainability and scalability for the web application.\n\n## 🔨 What I Built\n\nThe core of this project is the Flask application factory. This factory is responsible for:\n\n- **Application Instance Creation**: Generating and configuring the Flask application instance.\n- **Configuration Loading**: Handling the loading of application configurations.\n- **Blueprint Registration**: Registering various Flask Blueprints, which allows for a modular and organized structure of the application\'s routes and functionalities.\n\n## 💭 Thought Process\n\nI adopted the application factory pattern to ensure a clean and scalable architecture for the Flask application. This decision was made to facilitate easier testing, management of different environments (e.g., development, production), and the modularization of features using Flask Blueprints. While database initialization is currently commented out, the structure allows for straightforward integration of a database in the future without significant refactoring. The use of blueprints makes it simple to add new features as independent modules, keeping the codebase organized and understandable.\n\n## 🛠️ Tools & Tech Stack\n\n| Layer     | Technology      |\n|-----------|-----------------|\n| Framework | Flask           |\n| Extension | Flask Blueprint |\n\n## 🚀 Getting Started\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Python 3.x\n\n### Installation\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.rashadmin/codecreator.git\ncd codecreator\npip install Flask\n```\n\n### Run\n\n```bash\n# Assuming you have a file that calls the create_app() function,\n# for example, a run.py file:\n# from app import create_app\n# app = create_app()\n# if __name__ == \'__main__\':\n#     app.run(debug=True)\n\nexport FLASK_APP=app\nflask run\n```\n\n## 📖 Usage\n\nThis project sets up the foundation for a Flask application. Developers can extend it by creating new blueprints and registering them within the `create_app` function in `app/__init__.py`.\n\n### Example: Adding a new blueprint\n\n```python\n# In app/__init__.py\nfrom flask import Flask, Blueprint\n\ndef create_app():\n    app = Flask(__name__)\n    # ... configuration ...\n\n    from .main import main_bp\n    app.register_blueprint(main_bp)\n\n    return app\n\n# In app/main.py\nfrom flask import Blueprint, render_template\n\nmain_bp = Blueprint(\'main\', __name__)\n\n@main_bp.route(\'/\')\ndef index():\n    return "Hello from CodeCreator!"\n```\n\n## 📚 Resources\n\n- [Flask Documentation](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/latest/)\n\n## 📄 License\n\nMIT © [rashadmin](https://github.com/rashadmin)', 'path': 'README.md', 'branch': 'master', 'repo': 'codecreator', 'owner': 'rashadmin', 'message': 'docs: add README generated by readme-agent'}}
