2026-04-02 17:21:40,310 | INFO | readme_agent_api | [AGENT] Tool call: create_or_update_file | args: {'content': '# Rapid Care Hub\n\n> An AI-powered interactive chatbot for medical emergencies, providing real-time assistance and simulating hospital dispatches.\n\n## 🧠 Overview\n\nThe Rapid Care Hub is a Streamlit-based application designed to offer immediate support during medical emergencies. It acts as an intelligent assistant, capturing critical patient and emergency details, processing them with advanced AI, and simulating the dispatch of this vital information to nearby hospitals. The project aims to bridge the gap between an emergency occurring and professional help arriving, by providing timely guidance and facilitating rapid information dissemination to medical facilities.\n\n## 🔨 What I Built\n\nThis project delivers a comprehensive emergency response system that empowers users with crucial support:\n\n-   **AI-Powered Emergency Triage**: Leverages OpenAI\'s GPT models to interpret natural language descriptions of medical emergencies, classify conditions, and recommend appropriate medical specialists.\n-   **Interactive Chatbot Interface**: A user-friendly Streamlit interface guides users through the process of reporting an emergency, collecting essential patient demographics and situation details.\n-   **Simulated Hospital Dispatch System**: Simulates the real-time dispatch of emergency information to a network of hospitals, dynamically tracking their acceptance status and proximity.\n-   **First-Aid Guidance**: Provides immediate access to vital first-aid instructions through curated YouTube video links for critical procedures like CPR.\n-   **Dynamic Hospital & Patient Dashboard**: Features a dedicated page to display structured patient data, physician recommendations, symptoms, and the current situation, with conditional styling for urgent cases.\n-   **Content Management**: An "About" page allows users to toggle between a technical description of the project and a general overview, enhancing user understanding.\n\n## 💭 Thought Process\n\nMy approach focused on creating an intuitive and responsive emergency assistant. I chose **Streamlit** for the frontend due to its ability to rapidly build interactive web applications with minimal code, allowing me to concentrate on core functionalities. The decision to integrate **OpenAI\'s GPT models** was central to the project, as it enabled the sophisticated natural language processing required to understand diverse emergency descriptions and provide intelligent classifications and recommendations.\n\nA key design challenge was managing concurrency within the Streamlit environment, as both user interactions and background simulations needed to run smoothly. I addressed this by utilizing **Python\'s `threading` module** to handle tasks like the hospital dispatch simulation without blocking the main UI thread, ensuring a fluid user experience.\n\nFor data management, I opted for a straightforward approach using **local JSON and text files** to store hospital data, emergency history, and video links. While not a full-fledged database, this provided sufficient persistence for the project\'s scope. To optimize performance in Streamlit, I made extensive use of `st.session_state` to maintain application state across reruns and `st.cache_data` for memoizing function results, preventing unnecessary re-computation.\n\nFinally, I prioritized a modular design, breaking down complex logic into dedicated utility functions (e.g., `functions.py` for AI interaction and data generation, `clean.py` for text processing, `info.py` for resource links). This promotes reusability, maintainability, and a clearer separation of concerns throughout the codebase.\n\n## 🛠️ Tools & Tech Stack\n\n| Layer      | Technology          |\n|------------|---------------------|\n| Language   | Python 3            |\n| Framework  | Streamlit           |\n| AI / LLM   | OpenAI API (GPT-3.5-turbo) |\n| UI         | Bootstrap 4         |\n| Libraries  | NumPy, JSON, Threading, Random, sys |\n| Development| Jupyter Notebook (for debugging/experimentation) |\n\n## 🚀 Getting Started\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Python >= 3.8\n- An OpenAI API Key\n\n### Installation\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/rashadmin/Rapid_Transit_hub.git\ncd Rapid_Transit_hub\npip install streamlit openai numpy\n```\n\n### Environment Variables\n\nCreate a `secrets.toml` file in the `.streamlit` directory (you might need to create this directory) or a `.env` file in the root directory:\n\n```env\nOPENAI_API_KEY=your_openai_api_key_here\n```\n\n### Run\n\n```bash\nstreamlit run chatbot.py\n```\nor\n```bash\nstreamlit run rch.py\n```\n\n## 📖 Usage\n\n### Example 1: Reporting an Emergency via Chatbot\n\nInteract with the main chatbot interface to report a medical emergency. The AI will guide you through providing necessary details.\n\n```python\n# Assuming the Streamlit app is running,\n# users will interact directly via the web interface.\n# The chatbot will prompt for:\n# - Situation description\n# - Age\n# - Gender\n# - Surgical Status\n# - Trauma Name\n# - Trauma Description (if applicable)\n\n# The AI will then process this information and simulate hospital dispatch.\n```\n\n### Example 2: Viewing Hospital & Patient Details\n\nNavigate to the "Hospital" page to see the classified patient information, recommended physicians, symptoms, and the status of hospital dispatches.\n\n```markdown\n# Within the Streamlit application, click on the "Hospital" page in the sidebar.\n# This will display a dashboard similar to:\n#\n# Situation: <Emergency Description>\n# Age: <Patient Age>\n# Gender: <Patient Gender>\n# Surgical Status: <Yes/No>\n# Trauma Name: <Name>\n# Trauma Description: <Description>\n#\n# Physicians:\n# - Dr. Smith (Cardiologist)\n# - Dr. Jones (Emergency Medicine)\n#\n# Symptoms:\n# - Chest Pain\n# - Shortness of breath\n#\n# Hospital Dispatch Status:\n# Hospital A: Accepted (5 km away)\n# Hospital B: Pending (12 km away)\n```\n\n### Example 3: Accessing First-Aid Guidance\n\nOn the main emergency page, first-aid video links will appear based on the situation, allowing immediate access to critical life-saving instructions.\n\n```markdown\n# If the emergency involves, for example, cardiac arrest, a link like:\n#\n# [Watch CPR Adult Video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A2Wp9z7nFkY)\n#\n# will be displayed, which the user can click to learn basic life support.\n```\n\n## 📚 Resources\n\n-   [Streamlit Documentation](https://docs.streamlit.io/) — Python web app framework\n-   [OpenAI API Documentation](https://platform.openai.com/docs/api-reference) — LLM API reference\n-   [Python Threading Documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/threading.html) — Concurrency in Python\n-   [NumPy Documentation](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/) — Numerical computing library\n-   [Python JSON Module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/json.html) — JSON encoding/decoding\n-   [Bootstrap 4 Documentation](https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.6/) — UI framework for HTML/CSS\n\n## 📄 License\n\nMIT © [rashadmin](https://github.com/rashadmin)', 'owner': 'rashadmin', 'branch': 'master', 'message': 'docs: add README generated by readme-agent', 'path': 'README.md', 'repo': 'Rapid_Transit_hub', 'sha': '23078c875e9a9dad6bfc6426eade17d4ad66c505'}
